ages of justice, such as campaigns and the role of the media and the Court of Appeal and the Criminal Cases Review Commission (CCRC), they highlight criticism of the activities and decision-making of the latter and examine changes to police investigation in this area. Designed to incorporate ‘evidence-based policing’, each chapter provides questions reflecting on the issues raised in the text and suggestions for further reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCriminal justice, Administration of. 0aEvidence, Criminal. 0aJudicial error. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aMilne, Rebecca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMilne, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNurse, Angus, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNurse, Angus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoyser, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311119666440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447327455423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447327455/original  a978-3-11-119666-4  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK